n disappearance and erasure—a kind of fatal performance that left nothing behind but its self-effacing poetics. Bringing together dramatic theory, performance studies, and theatrical, religious, and cultural history, MacKay reveals the period’s radical take on the history and the future of the stage to show just how critical the relation was between early modern English theater and its public.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aEnglish drama -- Early modern and Elizabethan, 1500-1600 -- History and criticism. 0aEnglish dramayEarly modern and Elizabethan, 1500-1600xHistory and criticism. 0aTheater -- England -- History -- 16th century. 0aTheater -- Moral and ethical aspects -- England. 0aTheaterxMoral and ethical aspectszEngland. 0aTheaterzEnglandxHistoryy16th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  afugitive, refugee, early modern, history, historical, england, britain, united kingdom, western world, europe, theater, theatrical, shakespeare, stage, performance, globe, playhouse, plague, disease, abolition, cromwell, actor, actress, playwright, golden age, erasure, drama, dramatic, study, academic, scholarly, research, theory, analysis, culture, cultural, religion, faith, audience, rome, church.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226500218423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226500218/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles